f rulers that inadvertently led Bahrain, Qatar and the UAE to take their current shapes. The story addresses the crucial question of self-determination versus 'better together', a dilemma pertinent to anyone interested in the transformation of the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aDecolonisation.  aEast of Suez.  aImperial and global history.  aInformal empire.  aPersian Gulf.  aRoy Jenkins.  aSovereignty.  aStandardisation.  aTrucial States.  aUnited Arab Emirates.1 aSato, Shohei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499732840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784997328423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784997328/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packageb2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles